<subSubSection id="C30800BD35619972FF46FF532BC5ED9E" pageId="1" pageNumber="189" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAD533635619972FF46FF532BC5ED9E" blockId="1.[136,1452,172,486]" pageId="1" pageNumber="189">
Allied to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1228B535619972FF2DFF532A7DED0E" authority="Dalzell" authorityName="Dalzell" box="[227,530,248,270]" class="Liliopsida" family="Eriocaulaceae" genus="Eriocaulon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cuspidatum">
<emphasis id="B9668F2435619972FF2DFF5329AAED0D" box="[227,453,248,269]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="189">Eriocaulon cuspidatum</emphasis>
Dalzell
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in its broadly cuneate floral bracts that are densely hoary dorsally towards apex (vs. oblanceolate, sparsely hoary dorsally towards apex), narrowly keeled sepals of male flowers (vs. not keeled), obovate, conduplicate, broadly keeled sepals of female flowers that are smooth along margin, densely hairy along keel and on dorsal side (vs. oblanceolate, conduplicate, acuminate, keeled, scarious, glabrous), and unequal, linear to lanceolate petals of female flowers that are hoary at apex in odd petal (vs. subequal, spathulate, sparsely hoary at apex in all the petals).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
